benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: GET /1.0/kb/accounts/{accountId}/allTags - Retrieve account tags

covered: Valid Request: 200 response with JSON array of Tag objects; Tag schema asserted (TC01).
Default behaviors: excluded deleted tags and audit=NONE by default (TC01).
Query Parameters (valid): objectType filtering (INVOICE, PAYMENT), includedDeleted, audit=FULL/MINIMAL/NONE, and combined usage (TC02, TC03, TC04, TC05, TC06, TC20, TC21).
Empty Response: account with no tags returns empty array (TC07).
Path param validation: malformed UUID -> 400; non-existent/soft-deleted/not in DB -> 404 (TC08, TC09, TC25, TC26).
Unsupported/invalid query inputs: unknown param ignored (TC13); invalid audit value -> 400 (TC22).
Security hardening: SQL injection in accountId rejected without info leakage (TC12).
Performance/Load: large dataset returns within threshold and includes all tags (TC14); concurrency returns consistent 200s (TC23).
Integration consistency: after POST/DELETE operations, GET reflects changes including deleted with includedDeleted=true (TC18, TC19).
Backward compatibility: no-parameter behavior equals defaults (TC17).
gaps: Pagination: No explicit verification of pagination semantics or explicit absence (e.g., Link headers, page params) with large datasets.
Caching behavior: No tests for ETag/Last-Modified/Cache-Control headers or 304 via If-None-Match/If-Modified-Since.
Rate limiting/throttling: No scenarios asserting 429 Too Many Requests or related headers (Retry-After, rate-limit headers).
Authorization 403: No test for authenticated but unauthorized user (forbidden).
Query parameter negatives incomplete: no invalid objectType enum value or case sensitivity tests; no invalid type for includedDeleted (e.g., includedDeleted=foo).
Audit level detail: scenarios do not assert exact audit fields present/absent per NONE/MINIMAL/FULL; only high-level statements.
Deleted tag metadata: tests include deleted tags but do not validate correct flags/fields indicating deletion state.
Error payload schema: tests look for messages but not the standardized error structure (e.g., code, message, type).
Content negotiation: no test for Accept header handling (e.g., 406 Not Acceptable) or charset in Content-Type.
Observability in TC24: expectation to “log a warning” is not verifiable in test assertions (no log/metric/diagnostic header checks).
recommendations: Add pagination-focused tests: assert absence of pagination (no Link/X-Total-Count) if not supported, or validate page/size parameters and boundaries if supported. Use large dataset to confirm deterministic behavior.
Add caching tests: capture ETag/Last-Modified on first call; send If-None-Match/If-Modified-Since to expect 304; verify Cache-Control/ETag presence and correctness.
Introduce rate-limiting scenarios: burst requests to trigger 429, validate Retry-After and any rate-limit headers; ensure normal throughput is unaffected.
Add 403 Forbidden test: valid auth but lacking permission/role should yield 403 with proper error body.
Expand negative parameter tests: objectType=INVALID -> 400; objectType case variations; includedDeleted with non-boolean values -> 400; repeated parameters precedence.
Strengthen audit assertions: explicitly validate which audit fields are present for FULL vs MINIMAL and absent for NONE per Tag schema.
Validate deleted tag markers: assert deleted flag/timestamps/user for includedDeleted=true, and confirm absence when includedDeleted=false.
Standardize error response checks: verify error schema fields (e.g., code, message, category) for 400/404/401/503/504 across scenarios.
Test content negotiation: request with unacceptable Accept header to expect 406, and verify charset in Content-Type when applicable.
Make TC24 testable: add assertions on deterministic API behavior (e.g., last-write-wins rule, conflict resolution) and verify logs via observable proxies or diagnostic headers/metrics.
